<header class="header">
  <h1>Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Calendar days measure time. Crops develop based on heat.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    A seed packet might say “90 days to maturity.”
    In a short growing season, that number can appear reassuring.
    But in cold climates, development speed depends on accumulated heat —
    not calendar days alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    When seasonal heat accumulation is limited,
    a crop can run out of usable heat before it runs out of days.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Core Problem With “Days to Maturity”</h2>

  <p>
    Days to maturity assumes average temperature conditions.
    It estimates how long a crop takes to reach harvest under typical warmth.
  </p>

  <p>
    But “average warmth” is not universal.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two locations can both have:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>100 frost-free days</li>
    <li>A crop labeled 90 days to maturity</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Yet one location may accumulate enough heat for maturity —
    and the other may not.
  </p>

  <p>
    The difference is not the calendar.
    It is the seasonal heat budget inside the frost boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Boundaries Define the Window</h2>

  <p>
    Every growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Last spring frost</strong></li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost dates are based on <strong>1991–2020 climate normals</strong>
    and typically expressed at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    That means about half of years will see frost earlier or later than the listed date.
  </p>

  <p>
    Inside that frost-free window,
    crops must accumulate enough heat to complete development.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you don’t know your frost boundaries,
    start with the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crops Develop Based on Accumulated Heat</h2>

  <p>
    Most warm-season crops develop in proportion to temperature above a base threshold.
    This is measured using Growing Degree Days (GDD).
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    The base of 50°F (10°C) is commonly used for crops like tomatoes, peppers, and corn.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each day that temperatures exceed this base contributes heat units.
    Over time, those units accumulate into your seasonal heat budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cold climates, accumulation is slower —
    even when frost-free days appear sufficient.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Heat Deficit Problem</h2>

  <p>
    A crop labeled “90 days to maturity” may require approximately 1,600–1,800 GDD.
  </p>

  <p>
    In a warm climate that accumulates 2,200 GDD before fall frost,
    the crop matures comfortably.
  </p>

  <p>
    In a cool climate that accumulates only 1,500 GDD,
    the crop experiences a heat deficit.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even if 100 calendar days pass,
    insufficient heat accumulation delays physiological maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    The frost boundary arrives.
    The crop remains unfinished.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Applied Scenario Modeling</h2>

  <p><strong>Scenario A — 2,400 GDD Available</strong><br>
  A 1,600 GDD tomato matures reliably.<br>
  A 2,100 GDD heirloom still has margin.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario B — 1,800 GDD Available</strong><br>
  A 1,400 GDD variety matures comfortably.<br>
  A 1,800 GDD variety becomes borderline.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario C — 1,400 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Short-season varieties may mature.<br>
  Long-season crops are structurally mismatched.</p>

  <p>
    Notice that calendar days may be similar across scenarios.
    Heat accumulation determines outcome.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why This Matters More in Cold Climates</h2>

  <p>
    In long, warm seasons, heat accumulation often exceeds crop requirements by a wide margin.
    Days-to-maturity labels appear reliable because margin absorbs variability.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short or cool climates:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Spring warms slowly.</li>
    <li>Summer nights may remain cool.</li>
    <li>Fall frost can arrive early.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Each of these reduces effective heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Near the frost boundary,
    small deficits compound.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin: Comfortable vs Borderline</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable:</strong> Seasonal GDD exceeds crop requirement by several hundred units.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline:</strong> Seasonal GDD closely matches requirement.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely:</strong> Seasonal GDD typically falls short.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because frost timing uses probability framing,
    cooler-than-typical summers or earlier-than-typical fall frosts reduce margin further.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cold climates, operating without margin is risky.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Replace Calendar Thinking With Climate Modeling</h2>

  <p>
    A more reliable planning sequence is:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify frost boundaries (32°F, 50% probability).</li>
    <li>Define your frost-free window.</li>
    <li>Estimate seasonal GDD before first frost.</li>
    <li>Compare crop heat requirements.</li>
    <li>Choose your risk margin.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    You can estimate available seasonal heat using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a broader explanation of how frost timing and heat accumulation interact, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    When planning in short climates,
    this modeling approach replaces guesswork with measurable constraints.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Days to maturity assumes average warmth.</li>
    <li>Cold climates accumulate heat more slowly.</li>
    <li>Frost boundaries define the time window.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days define the heat budget.</li>
    <li>Crop success depends on margin before frost returns.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In cold climates, calendar labels can conceal heat deficits.
    Climate-based planning reveals them.
  </p>
</section>